        "48. Bergholm V , Izaac J, Schuld M, Gogolin C, Ahmed S, Ajith V , Alam MS, Alonso-Linaje G, Akash- Narayanan B, Asadi A, et al (2018) Pennylane: Automatic differentiation of hybrid quantum-classical computations. arXiv preprint arXiv:1811.04968 Publisher’s Note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional afﬁliations. Springer Nature or its licensor (e.g. a society or other partner) holds exclusive rights to this article under a publishing agreement with the author(s) or other rightsholder(s); author self-archiving of the accepted manuscript version of this article is solely governed by the terms of such publishing agreement and applicable law. 123 Quantum recurrent neural network for sequential labeling Page 23 of 23    84 Shyambabu Pandey is a Ph.D. Scholar in the Department of Com- puter Science and Engineering at the National Institute of Technology Silchar, India. His research focuses on quantum computing, quantum machine learning, and natural language processing. He is particularly interested in developing quantum machine learning models for natural language processing applications. Partha Pakray is an Associate Professor in the Department of Com- puter Science & Engineering at the National Institute of Technology Silchar. He worked as a Postdoctoral Fellow in the Natural Language Processing (NLP) domain at Masaryk University, Czech Republic. He was also a Postdoctoral Fellow at the Norwegian University of Sci- ence and Technology from 2013 to 2014. He worked as a Senior Research Engineer at Jadavpur University on the “Development of Cross-Lingual Information Access (CLIA) Phase II” project under the Ministry of Communications & Information Technology, Govern- ment of India (2007-2013). His international collaborations include the CONACYT-DST India project titled “Answer V alidation through Textual Entailment” with Alexander Gelbukh from the National Poly- technic Institute, Mexico, and Professor Sivaji Bandyopadhyay from Jadavpur University, India. He visited Mexico in 2011 and 2013 for this project. In 2012, Partha Pakray completed a six-month research intern- ship at Xerox Research Centre Europe (XRCE) in Grenoble, France. He got the workshop project funding on “Quantum Machine Learning for Natural Language Processing Applications” from MeitY Quantum Computing Applications Lab (QCAL). His research expertise focuses on quantum machine learning for natural language processing application. He has published more than 150 papers in reputed journals, conferences and workshops proceedings, and 5 patents. He received 8 research funded projects from various Government of India funding agencies like DST, SERB, CEFIPRA, DAAD, ASEAN, and MeitY Quantum Computing Applications Lab (QCAL). He is very active in several interna- tional conferences organized by local and international associations, institutions, or universities and is also an editorial board member of Natural Language Engineering (Cambridge Press) journal. Fabio Massimo Zanzotto is an Italian researcher in artiﬁcial intelli- gence, active in NLP and machine learning since 1998. He has served as an Associate Professor in the Department of Enterprise Engineering at the University of Rome “Tor V ergata” since 2006. His research cen- ters on four main areas: actionable explainability for machine learning models (including NLP and medical applications), Ethics & AI (includ- ing a manifesto advocating “fair AI” that repays the knowledge it uses), AI for precision medicine, and recognizing textual entailment (includ- ing a book and multiple papers). He has led and contributed to several funded research initiatives, including roles in projects such as SMART- BENCH, SFIdA Now, REVERT (H2020), and as Principal Investigator for KA TY (Horizon 2020), STEP , and Class-tAIs (PRIN-2022). His work has also been featured in national media and cultural press outlets (e.g., RAI Scuola and major Italian newspapers). 123"
